{{nihongo foot|'''''Famicom Detective Club'''''|ファミコン探偵倶楽部|Famicom Tantei Club|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is an [[adventure game]] duology developed and published by [[Nintendo]] for the [[Famicom Disk System|Family Computer Disk System]]. The first entry, {{nihongo foot|'''''The Missing Heir''''',|消えた後継者|Kieta Kōkeisha|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} was released in 1988, followed by a prequel released the next year titled {{nihongo foot|'''''The Girl Who Stands Behind'''''.|うしろに立つ少女|Ushiro ni Tatsu Shōjo|also known as ''Famicom Tantei Club Part II''|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} In both games, the player takes on the role of a young man solving murder mysteries in the Japanese countryside.

The duology was the first writing project for [[Yoshio Sakamoto]], before he found greater success and recognition with ''[[Metroid]]''. The games were inspired by [[Enix]]'s 1983 adventure game ''[[The Portopia Serial Murder Case]]'', horror films by Italian director [[Dario Argento]], and detective novels by Japanese writer [[Seishi Yokomizo]]. Both games were only released in Japan and received positive reception from critics.

Nintendo revisited the series on the [[Super Famicom]] with a remake of ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'' and an episodic [[Satellaview]] broadcast featuring a new story, ''BS Tantei Club: Yuki ni Kieta Kako''. In 2021, Nintendo released new remakes of ''The Missing Heir'' and ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'' for the [[Nintendo Switch]], developed by [[Mages (company)|Mages]]. The remakes were [[Video game localization|localized]] and released outside Japan.

== Gameplay ==
[[File:FamicomDetectiveClub_screenshot_Heir.png|thumb|left|The player speaks with Ayumi Tachibana in ''The Missing Heir'' (Disk System version)]]
In ''Famicom Detective Club'', the player chooses commands from a menu such as ''Ask'', ''Examine'', ''Take'', ''Show'', and ''Go'' to interact with the environment and characters.<ref name="HG101FDC:TMH">{{cite web|last=Brink|first=Daniel|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/famicom-detective-club-the-missing-heir/|title=Famicom Detective Club: The Missing Heir|publisher=Hardcore Gaming 101|date=May 19, 2021|access-date=2021-05-19|archive-date=2021-05-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210519170558/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/famicom-detective-club-the-missing-heir/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="HG101FDC:TGSitB">{{cite web|last=Brink|first=Daniel|url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/famicom-detective-club-part-ii-the-girl-standing-in-the-back/|title=Famicom Detective Club Part II: The Girl Standing in the Back|publisher=Hardcore Gaming 101|date=May 21, 2021|access-date=2021-05-21|archive-date=2021-05-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210521163650/http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/famicom-detective-club-part-ii-the-girl-standing-in-the-back/|url-status=live}}</ref> Character dialogue is displayed in a message box at the bottom of the screen. Commands are only listed in situations when they can be used. Some commands like ''Examine'' or ''Take'' place a cursor over the scene which the player can direct to an item or area to interact with. At certain points in the story, the player is asked to answer questions, and must scroll through letters to write out an answer.<ref name="HG101FDC:TMH"/><ref name="HG101FDC:TGSitB"/> The player may save their progress to return to the game later when the option is listed in the command menu.<ref name="HG101FDC:TMH"/><ref>{{Cite web|title=VC ファミコン探偵倶楽部PART II うしろに立つ少女（前後編）|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_fct2z/vc_fct2z_03.html|access-date=2021-02-21|website=www.nintendo.co.jp|archive-date=2015-07-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150718062837/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_fct2z/vc_fct2z_03.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Plot ==
===''The Missing Heir''===
The story begins with a man, Amachi, discovering the fallen protagonist on the ground near a cliff. The protagonist discovers that he has lost his memory, and after recuperating, he revisits the cliff and meets a young girl named Ayumi Tachibana. He learns from Ayumi that he is an assistant detective investigating the death of Kiku Ayashiro, and heads over to the nearby Ayashiro estate located in Myoujin village. The Ayashiro family owns a huge plot of land passed down from generation to generation, but there is a strange saying in the village that the dead will return to life to kill anyone who attempts to steal the treasure of the Ayashiro family. As the protagonist investigates the mysterious death of Kiku Ayashiro, he discovers the terrifying connection between this saying and the [[serial killing]]s which take place.

===''The Girl Who Stands Behind''===
Three years before the events of ''The Missing Heir'',<ref name=":3">{{cite web|last=Hernandez|first=Carlos|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/07/05/famicom-detective-club-part-ii-the-girl-who-stands-behind/|title=Famicom Detective Club Part II: The Girl who Stands Behind|publisher=[[VentureBeat]]|date=July 5, 2011|access-date=2021-02-19|archive-date=2021-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514221215/https://venturebeat.com/2011/07/05/famicom-detective-club-part-ii-the-girl-who-stands-behind/|url-status=live}}</ref> The protagonist, a 15-year-old boy, escapes his orphanage to look for his parents. Two police officers chase after the protagonist until Shunsuke Utsugi, a private detective respected by the police, takes him in as an assistant.

A few months later, Utsugi and the protagonist are called to investigate the murder of freshman schoolgirl Yoko Kojima. The protagonist begins gathering information from Ushimitsu High School to solve the Yoko case and connect it with the Genjiro Kaneda case along with the help of Yoko's two high school friends; a girl named Ayumi Tachibana and a boy named Hitomi Kawaii. It soon emerges that Yoko was deep into an investigation of "The Tale of the Girl Who Stands Behind," a rumor involving a ghost of a blood-soaked girl that stands behind a student, and the trio set out to discover the truth behind this rumor.

== Development ==
[[File:Yoshio Sakamoto - Game Developers Conference 2010 - Day 3 (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|right|Writer [[Yoshio Sakamoto]] in 2010]]
The duology was written by [[Yoshio Sakamoto]].<ref name=":4">{{cite web|last=Bivens|first=Danny|url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/33985/japan-eshop-round-up-04242013|title=Japan eShop Round-Up (04/24/2013) - Feature|work=Nintendo World Report|publisher=NINWR, LLC|date=April 26, 2013|access-date=2021-02-19|archive-date=2021-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514222528/https://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/33985/japan-eshop-round-up-04242013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":6">{{cite web|url=https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2013/04/17/65660.html|title=任天堂の名作アドベンチャー『ファミコン探偵倶楽部 消えた後継者』3DSVCで配信決定|work=Inside Games|publisher=IID, Inc.|date=April 17, 2013|access-date=2021-02-19|language=ja|archive-date=2021-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514221215/https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2013/04/17/65660.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The games were his first experience with scenario writing,<ref name=":8" /> and he considers it a turning point in his career.<ref name=":7" /> Sakamoto would later become more well known for his work on the ''[[Metroid]]'' series.<ref name=":2" />

Development of the games began when [[Gunpei Yokoi]] asked Sakamoto to develop a game titled ''Famicom Shōnen Tanteidan'' (Famicom Youth Detective Group) with another company. The game would ultimately become ''Famicom Detective Club.''<ref name=":8">{{cite web|last=Iwata|first=Satoru|author-link=Satoru Iwata|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Iwata-Asks/Iwata-Asks-Metroid-Other-M/Iwata-Asks-Yoshio-Sakamoto-Hironobu-Sakaguchi/2-Stories-in-Computer-Games-/2-Stories-in-Computer-Games--218066.html|title=Iwata Asks: Metroid: Other M|work=[[Iwata Asks]]|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|date=26 August 2010|page=2|access-date=2021-02-19|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200929054934/https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Iwata-Asks/Iwata-Asks-Metroid-Other-M/Iwata-Asks-Yoshio-Sakamoto-Hironobu-Sakaguchi/2-Stories-in-Computer-Games-/2-Stories-in-Computer-Games--218066.html|archive-date=2020-09-29|url-status=live}}</ref> Only being given the title as a foundation, Sakamoto pulled inspiration from ''[[The Portopia Serial Murder Case]]'' (1983) to create a text-based adventure game with a tight story.<ref name=":8" /> Early in development, Sakamoto briefly worked on the dating sim ''[[Nakayama Miho no Tokimeki High School]]'' (1987), which had a troubled development due to the involvement of [[Miho Nakayama]] and using the [[Alfa DiskFax|Disk Fax]] network. Sakamoto made sure to avoid those frustrations when developing ''Famicom Detective Club''.<ref name="Continuev10">{{cite magazine|last=Tane|first=Kiyoshi|date=June 18, 2003|title=坂本 賀勇 - 『メトロイド』を創った男|magazine=Continue|publisher=[[Ohta Publishing]]|volume=10|pages=138–139|isbn=978-4872337709|lang=ja}}</ref>

Before development began in earnest, Sakamoto handwrote the scenario in book form and shared it with the staff.<ref name="Continuev10"/> The scenario was originally titled ''Corpse Village'' (屍の村, ''Shikabane no Mura''), but Sakamoto was convinced to change it after showing the proposal to his boss.<ref name="NinDori">{{cite magazine|title=ファミコンディスクシステム 2: 遊べば遊ぶほど遊びたくなる [ディスク2]|trans-title=Famicom Disk System: The More You Play It, the More You'll Want to Play (Disk 2)|magazine=Nintendo Dream|language=ja|volume=119|publisher=Mainichi Communications|date=September 21, 2004}} ([http://www.metroid-database.com/m1/fds-interview2-p3.php Translation] by Metroid Database. {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130407031808/http://www.metroid-database.com/m1/fds-interview2-p3.php|date=2013-04-07}}).</ref> Sakamoto explained in a retrospective interview that for games with deep stories like adventure games, it is usually best to start development with the story as the root.<ref name="Continuev10" /> He considers the games an homage to Italian horror filmmaker [[Dario Argento]].<ref name=":7">{{cite web|last=Manabu|first=Tsuchimoto|url=https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2010/03/12/40968.html|title=【GDC2010】任天堂、坂本賀勇氏が初めて明かすゲーム作りのアプローチ|work=Inside|publisher=IID, Inc.|date=March 12, 2010|access-date=2021-02-19|language=ja|archive-date=2021-03-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210303084144/https://www.inside-games.jp/article/2010/03/12/40968.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{cite web|last=Alexander|first=Leigh|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/118578/GDC_Nintendos_Sakamotos_Four_Creative_Tenets.php|title=GDC: Nintendo's Sakamoto's Four Creative Tenets|work=[[Gamasutra]]|publisher=[[UBM Technology Group]]|date=March 11, 2010|access-date=2021-02-19|archive-date=2021-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514221215/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/118578/GDC_Nintendos_Sakamotos_Four_Creative_Tenets.php|url-status=live}}</ref> Reflecting on his early days at Nintendo, Sakamoto said he "wanted to create things in the same manner as Argento did."<ref name=":2" /> ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'' was inspired by Argento's method of connecting music and images in ''[[Deep Red]]'' (1975), Sakamoto's favorite movie.<ref name="Continuev10"/> Additionally, ''The Missing Heir'' took some inspiration from [[Seishi Yokomizo]]'s novels such as ''Inugamike no Ichizoku'' and ''Akuma no Temari Uta'', and the style of ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'' was inspired by [[shōjo manga]].<ref name="Continuev10" /><ref name="NinDori"/>

Writer Toru Osawa intended the packaging artwork for ''The Missing Heir'' to be similar to the posters of [[Toho]]'s Seishi Yokomizo films. However, Osawa and Sakamoto were dissatisfied with the final art, which was commissioned from a company outside Nintendo. As a result, for ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'', Osawa personally created a sketch and layout based on shōjo manga for the packaging artwork, which was completed by a professional artist.<ref name="NinDori"/>

Composer [[Kenji Yamamoto (composer born 1964)|Kenji Yamamoto]] recalled that he had aimed to use the Famicom's sound system to its fullest extent in ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'', and that Sakamoto had instructed him to make the final scene as scary as possible. To accomplish this, Yamamoto set the volume of the regular music to be about half of what normal games used, and then increased the volume to its maximum level for the final scene, so as to startle players.<ref name="NinDori"/>

== Release ==
''Famicom Detective Club'' was originally released for the [[Famicom Disk System|Family Computer Disk System]] across four disks. ''The Missing Heir'' was released across two disks on April 27 and June 14, 1988.<ref name=":6" /> ''The Girl Who Stands Behind'' was also released across two disks on May 23 and June 30, 1989.<ref name="DenFamGamer">{{cite web|author=Yukki P|url=https://news.denfaminicogamer.jp/horror2016/hr-review041|title=「学校を舞台にしたホラゲの先駆け的存在」『ファミコン探偵倶楽部 PART II うしろに立つ少女』【ホラゲレビュー百物語】|work=Den Faminico Gamer|publisher=Mare Inc.|date=August 5, 2016|access-date=2021-02-19|language=ja|archive-date=2021-05-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210514221217/https://news.denfaminicogamer.jp/horror2016/hr-review041|url-status=live}}</ref>

